{"title_page": "Mike Baird", "text_new": "{{short description|New South Wales politician and premier}}\n{{about|the Australian politician|other people called Mike or Michael Baird|Michael Baird (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix  = [[The Honourable]]\n| name             = Mike Baird \n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = File:The Honourable Mike Baird MP.png\n| imagesize        =\n| order1           = 44th [[Premier of New South Wales]]<br />{{small|Elections: [[2015 New South Wales state election|2015]]}}\n| term_start1      = 17 April 2014\n| term_end1        = 23 January 2017\n| monarch1         = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| governor1        = [[Marie Bashir]]<br />[[David Hurley]]\n| deputy1          = [[Andrew Stoner]] <br />[[Troy Grant]] <br />[[John Barilaro]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Barry O'Farrell]]\n| successor1       = [[Gladys Berejiklian]]\n| order2           = 20th [[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)#Parliamentary party leaders|Leader of the New South Wales Liberal Party]]\n| term_start2      = 17 April 2014\n| term_end2        = 23 January 2017\n| deputy2          = Gladys Berejiklian\n| predecessor2     = [[Barry O'Farrell]]\n| successor2       = Gladys Berejiklian\n| order3           = [[Minister for Planning (New South Wales)#Infrastructure|Minister for Infrastructure]]\n| term_start3      = 23 April 2014\n| term_end3        = 23 January 2017\n| predecessor3     = [[Brad Hazzard]]\n| successor3       = [[Andrew Constance]]\n| order4           = [[Minister for Jobs, Investment, Tourism and Western Sydney|Minister for Western Sydney]]\n| term_start4      = 23 April 2014\n| term_end4        = 23 January 2017\n| predecessor4     = [[Barry O'Farrell]]\n| successor4       = [[Stuart Ayres]]\n| order5           = [[Treasurer of New South Wales]]\n| term_start5      = 3 April 2011\n| term_end5        = 23 April 2014\n| premier5         = [[Barry O'Farrell]]\n| predecessor5     = [[Eric Roozendaal]]\n| successor5       = [[Andrew Constance]]\n| constituency_MP6 = [[Electoral district of Manly|Manly]]\n| parliament6      = New South Wales\n| term_start6      = [[2007 New South Wales state election|24 March 2007]]\n| term_end6        = 23 January 2017\n| predecessor6     = [[David Barr (politician)|David Barr]]\n| successor6       = [[James Griffin (Australian politician)|James Griffin]]\n| birth_name       = Michael Bruce Baird\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1968|4|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)|Liberal Party]]\n| relations        = [[Bruce Baird]] (father), [[Julia Baird (journalist)|Julia Baird]] (sister)\n| spouse           = Kerryn Baird\n| children         = 3\n| occupation       = [[Chief Customer Officer]] of [[National Australia Bank|NAB]]<br />[[Politician]]\n| religion         = [[Anglican Church of Australia|Anglican]]\n| education        = [[The King's School, Parramatta]]<br />[[University of Sydney]]<br />[[Regent College]]\n| signature        =\n| website          =\n| footnotes        = <ref>{{cite web|last=Korporaal|first=Glenda|title=Political son wants a big gig|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/political-son-wants-a-big-gig/story-fn59niix-1226000008332|work=[[The Australian]]|date=5 February 2011|publisher=News Limited|accessdate=26 April 2011}}</ref><ref name=guardianwhois>{{cite news|last=Jabour|first=Bridie|title=Who is Mike Baird? Meet NSW's new fiscally conservative Christian premier|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/apr/17/who-is-mike-baird-new-nsw-premier|accessdate=17 April 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 April 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Michael Bruce Baird''' (born 1 April 1968<ref>{{cite book |author1=Yeend, Peter Jon |author2=King's School (Parramatta, NSW) Council |title=The King's School register 1831\u20131999 |publication-date=2000 |publisher=Council of the King's School |edition=3rd |isbn=978-0-908234-06-6 }}</ref>) is an [[Australia]]n investment banker and former politician who was the 44th [[Premier of New South Wales]], the Minister for Infrastructure, the [[Minister for Jobs, Investment, Tourism and Western Sydney|Minister for Western Sydney]], and the [[Leader of the New South Wales Liberal Party]] from April 2014 to January 2017.\n\nBaird represented the [[electoral district of Manly]] in the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]] for the [[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)|Liberal Party]] from [[2007 New South Wales state election|2007]] to 2017. Before becoming Premier, he was the [[Treasurer of New South Wales]] in the [[Barry O'Farrell|O'Farrell]] [[O'Farrell ministry|government]] between 2011 and 2014. On 19 January 2017, Baird announced his intention to step down and on 23 January he resigned as Premier and member for Manly.\n\n==Early career==\nBorn in Melbourne, Baird is the son of Judy and [[Bruce Baird]].<ref name=guardianwhois/> His father was Deputy Leader of the New South Wales Liberal Party and Member of Parliament representing the [[electoral district of Northcott]], and later a Member of the [[Australian House of Representatives]], representing the [[Division of Cook]], for the Liberal Party.\n\nBaird attended [[The King's School, Parramatta]],<ref name=thesonrises /> and spent time living in the [[United States of America]] while his father served as head of the Australian trade commission in [[New York City]].<ref name=smhwhois/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sydneyanglicans.net/blogs/indepth/bruce_bairds_sweetest_victory|accessdate=15 November 2015|title=Early starters make real connections|first=Natasha|last=Percy|date=29 January 2009|publisher=Sydney Anglican Network}}</ref> Baird graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] with majors in Economics and Government from the [[University of Sydney]] in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sydney.edu.au/arts/economics/alumni/alumni-profiles.shtml|title=ECONOMICS ALUMNI PROFILES|publisher=The University of Sydney|quote=Mike BAIRD (BA \u201989).<br />Melbourne-born, Baird attended the King\u2019s School, Parramatta before undertaking his Sydney Arts degree with majors in Economics and Government.}}</ref><ref>{{cite NSW Parliament |id=40 |name=Mr (Mike) Michael Bruce BAIRD (1968 - ) |former=Yes |access-date=3 April 2019}}</ref> Baird also studied at [[Regent College]] in [[Vancouver|Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada, initially intending to enter the [[Anglican ministry]], but while there decided to pursue a career in investment banking and later politics.<ref name=thesonrises>{{cite web   | url  =  http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/the-son-rises-20121023-282ga.html   | title = The son rises   | last = Wood   | first = Stephanie   | work = Sydney Morning Herald   | date = 26 October 2012   | accessdate = 17 April 2014}}</ref> In 1999, he unsuccessfully sought preselection for the seat of Manly. Baird then returned to investment banking, working for the [[National Australia Bank]] for a time in [[London]], before returning to Sydney to work for [[HSBC]] Australia.<ref name=WOz-2011/>\n\n==Political career==\nBaird again sought, this time successfully, Liberal Party preselection for the seat of Manly and went on to defeat the sitting independent member [[David Barr (politician)|David Barr]] by 3.4% at the [[2007 New South Wales state election|2007 state election]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mikebaird.com.au/about/mike/about_mike.html |title=About Mike Baird |work=Member for Manly |publisher=Mike Baird |accessdate=11 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218103945/http://www.mikebaird.com.au/about/mike/about_mike.html |archive-date=18 February 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After initially serving in a range of junior shadow ministries, Baird was promoted to the position of Shadow Treasurer in 2008 and touted as a future Liberal leader.<ref name=WOz-2011>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/ex-banker-seeks-to-bring-balance-to-treasury-mike-baird-has-the-background-to-look-after-nsws-finances/story-e6frg8zx-1226028266126 |title=Ex-banker seeks to bring balance to Treasury: Mike Baird has the background to look after NSW's finances |work=[[The Australian|The Weekend Australian]] |date=26 March 2011 |author1=Cleary, Paul |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/ofarrells-heir-apparent-promoted/2008/12/27/1229998798654.html |title=Heir apparent promoted |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=28 December 2008 |author1=Lewis, Daniel |author2=Gibson, Joel |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref> Following the election of the O'Farrell government in 2011, Baird was appointed Treasurer, although O'Farrell removed some of Baird's ministerial responsibilities, transferring the authority for land tax, gaming tax, payroll tax, public service superannuation and the Office of State Revenue to [[Greg Pearce (politician)|Greg Pearce]], the Minister for Finance and Services.<ref name=Oz-2011>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/cupboard-is-baird-for-new-treasurer/story-fn3dxity-1226033790724 |title=Cupboard is Baird for new Treasurer as Barry O'Farrell 'neuters' department |work=[[The Australian]] |date=5 April 2011 |author1=Clennell, Andrew |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nBaird has campaigned against dangerous drinking, voted against embryonic stem research and euthanasia, does not support same-sex marriage or same-sex adoption<ref name=Onward>{{cite news |last=Nicholls |first=Sean |date=26 April 2014 |title=Onward Christian soldier: a premier's faith |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/onward-christian-soldier-a-premiers-faith-20140425-379pp.html |newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald }}</ref><ref name=smhwhois>{{cite news |author=Howden, Saffron |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/who-is-mike-baird-20140417-36ssh.html#ixzz2z5vnhpts |title=Who is Mike Baird? |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=17 April 2014 |accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref> and has stated that his strongest preference is not to support abortion in most circumstances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/the-new-face-of-the-liberals-charm-offensive/2008/12/29/1230399131583.html|title=The new face of the Liberals' charm offensive|last=Robins|first=Brian|date=30 December 2008|accessdate=24 February 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> He is strongly in favour of [[Republicanism in Australia|Australia becoming a republic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/apr/18/mike-baird-admits-mistake-appoint-nick-di-girolamo|title=Mike Baird admits mistake to appoint Nick de Girolamo to Sydney Water|last=Jabour|first=Bridie|work=The Guardian|date=18 April 2014|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Baird supported calls for increasing the [[Goods and Services Tax (Australia)|GST]] to 15%<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/tony-abbott-applauds-premier-mike-bairds-15-gst-proposal-20150720-gig34f.html</ref><ref>http://www.news.com.au/finance/economy/australian-economy/would-you-pay-more-push-to-raise-gst-to-15-per-cent/news-story/5b56a0ca3f2766e4d17ac567b7d1cce5</ref>\n\n===Premier of New South Wales===\n{{see also|Baird ministry (2014\u201315)|Second Baird ministry}}\n[[Image:(1)Lindt_Cafe_Reopening_035.jpg|thumb|left|Baird at the official [[2014 Sydney hostage crisis|reopening of the Lindt Caf\u00e9, Martin Place]], Sydney, March 2015.]]\n\nFollowing Barry O'Farrell's resignation,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/barry-ofarrell-quits-as-nsw-premier-over-memory-fail/story-fn59niix-1226886224077 |title=Barry O'Farrell quits as NSW Premier over memory fail |date=16 April 2014 |work=[[The Australian]] |accessdate=23 April 2014|first1=Leo|last1=Shanahan|first2=Mark|last2=Coultan}}</ref> Baird was elected unopposed as parliamentary leader of the NSW division of the Liberal Party on 17 April 2014, and subsequently sworn in as the 44th Premier of New South Wales on 23 April by the [[Governor of New South Wales]], [[Marie Bashir|Dame Marie Bashir]].<ref name=libleader>{{cite news|title=Mike Baird named new NSW premier named after Barry O'Farrell resignation|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-04-17/new-nsw-premier-named-after-ofarrell-resignation/5396584|accessdate=17 April 2014|newspaper=ABC News|date=17 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nBaird immediately reshuffled the ministry elevating [[Andrew Constance]] into the [[Treasurer of New South Wales|Treasury]] portfolio and increasing [[Andrew Stoner]]'s ministries to five <ref name=reshuffle>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/mike-bairds-cabinet-reshuffle-a-preparation-for-next-election-20140422-371g9.html?rand=1398136093991|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=14 November 2015|date=22 April 2014|title=Mike Baird's cabinet reshuffle a preparation for next election|first=Sean|last=Nicholls}}</ref> in preparation for the [[2015 New South Wales state election|2015 state election]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/mike-bairds-nsw-cabinet-20140422-371j4.html |title=Mike Baird's NSW cabinet |date=22 April 2014 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate=23 April 2014 }}</ref><ref name=reshuffle/> In October, Stoner resigned as Leader of the NSW Nationals and [[Deputy Premier of New South Wales]] and was replaced by [[Troy Grant]].\n\nThe ''Sydney Morning Herald'' described Baird's government as \"the most devout in living memory,\" with a concentration of powerful religious figures in its upper echelons.<ref name=Onward/> Baird's chief of staff, Bay Warburton, once said that in his role as chief of staff he is serving Jesus, \"and Mike (Baird), who's the Treasurer\u2014he believes he's serving Jesus as the Treasurer of the state. He believes that he has a great opportunity to help people by making responsible decisions about the money from this state.\"<ref name=Onward/>\n\nOn the morning of 15 December 2014, a lone gunman, [[Man Haron Monis]], [[2014 Sydney hostage crisis|held hostage ten customers and eight employees]] of a [[Lindt & Spr\u00fcngli|Lindt]] chocolate caf\u00e9 located at [[Martin Place, Sydney]]. Baird addressed the media during the stand-off, and stated \"we are being tested today... in Sydney. The police are being tested, the public is being tested, but whatever the test we will face it head on and we will remain a strong democratic, civil society. I have full confidence in the [[List of Commissioners of New South Wales Police|Police Commissioner]] and the incredible work of the [[New South Wales Police Force|NSW police force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QXYrHlBPX-k|title=Premier and Commissioner address the media re: Martin Place police operation|work=YouTube|accessdate=15 December 2014|date=15 December 2014}}</ref> On 20 March 2015, Baird met with staff at the re-opened caf\u00e9, stating the staff and company: \"...Are saying that they want to be strong for their friends, they want to be strong for this city and state\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-20/lindt-cafe-in-martin-place-reopens-after-deadly-siege/6334154|work=ABC News|title=Lindt cafe in Sydney's Martin Place reopens after deadly siege|first=Johanna|last=Nicholson|date=20 March 2015|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2015 New South Wales election====\n{{see also|New South Wales state election, 2015}}\n\nAt the 2015 election, Baird led the Liberal-National Coalition to a second term. The main policy that dominated the election was Baird's unpopular policy to lease 49% of the state's electricity distribution network, known as the \"poles and wires\" in the form of a 99-year lease to the private sector and use the proceeds to invest in new road, public transport, water, health and education infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/mike-bairds-electricity-dilemma-popular-premier-selling-a-toxic-electricity-privatisation-policy-20150306-13x13f.html|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=14 November 2014|date=7 March 2015|first1=Matt|last1=Wade|first2=Sean|last2=Nicholls|title=Mike Baird's electricity dilemma: popular Premier selling a toxic electricity privatisation policy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afr.com/news/coalition-premier-mike-baird-wins-nsw-election-20150328-1m9zxo|title=Coalition Premier Mike Baird wins NSW election|work=Financial Review|first1=Aaron|last1=Patrick|first2=Geoff|last2=Winestock|first3=Will|last3=Glasgow}}</ref>\n\nOther regional policies centred around the Baird Government's truncation of the [[Central Coast & Newcastle Line|Central Coast & Newcastle Railway Line]] at [[Wickham railway station, New South Wales|Wickham]] and its replacement with the $130 million [[Newcastle Light Rail|light rail system]] and associated [[Newcastle Interchange|transport interchange]] as part of a broader revitilisation of the [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]] city centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/nsw-state-election-2015/nsw-state-election-2015-the-train-that-divides-newcastle-20150225-13oflk.html|title=NSW State Election 2015: The train that divides Newcastle|first=Eryk|last=Bagshaw|date=4 March 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Heraldl|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref> [[Coal Seam Gas]] was a likewise major regional issue in northern New South Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-15/nationals-face-csg-backlash-northern-nsw-state-election/6319350|accessdate=14 November 2015|date=15 March 2015|work=ABC news|title=NSW election 2015: Nationals on edge in state's north over CSG backlash|first=Bruce|last=MacKenzie}}</ref>\n\nUltimately, Baird won a full term, though he lost 15 seats from the massive majority he'd inherited from O'Farrell. Baird is only the fourth state Liberal leader, after Sir [[Robert Askin]], [[Nick Greiner]] and O'Farrell, to win an election in New South Wales since the main non-Labor party adopted the [[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)|Liberal]] banner in 1945. It also marked the first time since [[1973 New South Wales state election|1973]] that a non-Labor government had retained its majority at an election and Baird became the first non-elected Liberal Premier to be elected in his own right.\n\n====Approval rating====\nSince replacing Barry O'Farrell as Premier in April 2014, Baird initially fared well in statewide opinion polls but his approval rating collapsed in the 2nd half of 2016. From December 2015 to September 2016, Baird's satisfaction rating fell by 46 points\u2014\"the biggest fall in net satisfaction of any mainland state premier in the history of Newspoll\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/newspoll/newspoll-dogs-ban-sends-mike-baird-ratings-into-freefall/news-story/91294495701cb40234d342cabd8c103b|first=Mark|last=Coultan|date=29 September 2016|work=The Australian|accessdate=1 December 2016|title=Newspoll: Dogs Ban Sends Mike Baird's Ratings Into Freefall}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:left; text-align:center; margin-right:.5em; margin-top:.4em; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n|+ '''Newspoll <br /> Satisfaction Rating of Mike Baird'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/state-politics/mike-baird-slumps-to-lowest-rating-as-coalition-clings-to-its-lead/news-story/3d2725e40d1cf002daa20eb9ce63186c|title=Mike Baird slumps to lowest rating as Coalition clings to its lead|work=The Australian|date=8 December 2016|first=Kylar|last=Loussikian|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n!\n! Satisfied\n! Dissatisfied \n|-\n! September 2016\n| style=|39%\n| style=|46% \n|-\n! September 2015\n| style=|63%\n| style=|23% \n|-   \n! March 2015\n| style=|57%\n| style=|29% \n|- \n! February 2015\n| style=|59%\n| style=|26% \n|- \n! December 2014\n| style=|60%\n| style=|22% \n|- \n! October 2014\n| style=|56%\n| style=|20% \n|- \n! August 2014\n| style=|49%\n| style=|23% \n|- \n! June 2014\n| style=|49%\n| style=|19% \n|- \n|}\n{{Clear}}\n\n====Lockout laws====\nBaird had publicly advocated for the tough [[Sydney lockout laws]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nsw.gov.au/newlaws |title=New alcohol laws now in place ShareTweet Sydney's alcohol laws |publisher=NSW Government |accessdate=21 Feb 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223141047/http://www.nsw.gov.au/newlaws |archivedate=23 February 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and on 9&nbsp;February 2016 posted a [[Facebook]] response to an article published by [[Matt Barrie]] condemning the Premier's actions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/matt-barries-tirade-against-sydneys-nighttime-regulations-goes-viral-20160203-gmlab1.html |title=Matt Barrie's tirade against Sydney's night-time lockout laws touches a raw nerve |publisher=Fairfax Media|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=21 Feb 2016|first=Daisy|last=Dumas}}</ref> Baird's response gained international attention<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-australia-35499522 |title=Sydney's lockout \u2018laughing stock' |publisher=BBC |accessdate=21 Feb 2016}}</ref> after the post received over 10,000 likes - along with more than 10,000 comments that were mostly critical of the Premier's stance on the laws.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/lockout-laws-nsw-premier-mike-baird-bombarded-on-facebook-and-twitter/news-story/0f627e978dd2002d9a86db9f460da65e |title=Lockout laws: NSW Premier Mike Baird bombarded on Facebook and Twitter |publisher=The Australian |accessdate=21 February 2016|first=Fred|last=Pawle|date=10 February 2016}}</ref> Baird's reputation as a \"darling of social media\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/thefeed/article/2016/02/10/mike-bairds-run-social-media-darling-goes-bust-casinomike |title=Mike Baird\u2019s run as social media darling goes bust with #casinomike |publisher=SBS |accessdate=21 February 2016|first=Maddie|last=Palmer|date=10 February 2016}}</ref> was tarnished as the hashtag #casinomike became the number one trending topic nationwide on [[Twitter]] in reference to lockout laws not applying to [[The Star, Sydney|Star City Casino]], as it is located outside the entertainment and cbd precincts where the laws apply.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/lockout-laws-star-attraction-inside-sydneys-biggest-afterhours-venue/news-story/521a30d553ce92b113b0c01178c34501 |title=Lockout laws\u2019 Star attraction: Inside Sydney\u2019s biggest after-hours venue|publisher=News.com |accessdate=21 February 2016|date=15 February 2016|first1=Emma|last1=Reynolds|first2=Andrew|last2=Koubaridis}}</ref> A protest was organised in response to Baird's comments by community group Keep Sydney Open on 21 February 2016,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/keep-sydney-open-protesters-march-to-unlock-sydneys-nightlife-20160221-gmzggk.html |title=Keep Sydney Open: protesters march to 'unlock Sydney's nightlife |publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=21 February 2016|first=Patrick|last=Begley|date=21 February 2016}}</ref> with over 15,000 people marching in Sydney's CBD and calling on the Baird government to abolish the lockout laws.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com.au/photos-15000-people-protest-lockout-laws-in-keep-sydney-open-rally-2016-2 |title=Photos: 15,000 people protest lockout laws in Keep Sydney Open rally |publisher=The Business Insider |accessdate=21 February 2016|first=Olivia|last=Chang|date=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Resignation====\nOn 19 January 2017, Baird announced he was retiring from politics, with his resignation to be effective after a [[leadership spill]] the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thesatellite.com.au/news/baird-resigns-nsw-premier-quit-top-job-and-parliam/3133375/|first=Owen|last=Jacques|title=Baird resigns: NSW Premier to quit top job and Parliament|work=The Satellite|date=19 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202002956/http://m.thesatellite.com.au/news/baird-resigns-nsw-premier-quit-top-job-and-parliam/3133375/|archivedate=2 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He said, \"I have made clear from the beginning that I was in politics to make a difference, and then move on. After 10 years in public life, this moment for me has arrived.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.9news.com.au/national/2017/01/19/09/08/nsw-premier-mike-baird-announces-resignation|work=9 News|date=19 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2017|title=NSW Premier Mike Baird brought to tears as he explains why he\u2019s quitting politics|first=Mary|last=Jordan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/politics/premier-mike-baird-resigns/news-story/c23b24d808dccecc654741106f9f64f7|title=Premier Mike Baird resigns|first=Kim|last=Stephens|work=news.com.au|date=19 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref> Following his decision to resign, Baird was criticised for his failure to listen on key issues such as protests against the [[WestConnex]], lockout laws and [[Local government areas of New South Wales#2010s|local government amalgamations]]. Baird also reversed an earlier decision to ban greyhound racing in the face of significant community pressure, especially from the Nationals.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Fernandez, Timothy |author2=Vukovic, Dom |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-01-20/mike-baird-resignation-thoughts-from-protesters-and-haters/8195434 |title=Mike Baird resignation: Thoughts from protesters and haters |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=20 January 2017 |access-date=23 January 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January 2017, Baird formally resigned as both premier and member for Manly, and [[Gladys Berejiklian]] was sworn in as New South Wales' 45th premier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-01-23/gladys-berejiklian-replaces-mike-baird-as-nsw-premier/8202820|title=Gladys Berejiklian is Premier of New South Wales, replacing Mike Baird|first=Clare|last=Blumer|date=23 January 2017|accessdate=26 January 2017|work=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n== Return to corporate life ==\nIn February 2017, Baird was appointed Chief Customer Officer at [[National Australia Bank]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-02-28/mike-baird-former-nsw-premier-takes-senior-nab-role/8309516|title=Mike Baird moves to NAB: Former NSW premier takes senior bank role|first=Michael|last=Janda|publisher=ABC|date=28 February 2017}}</ref> Baird was paid a total of A$2.29 million in 2018. In 2019, NAB executives forfeited their short-term bonuses, resulting in Baird earning the lesser total of A$1.7 million for that year. At the end of the 2018/2019 financial year, Baird held A$500,000 of NAB stock as well as 67,888 NAB performance rights, worth A$1.59 million as of March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://7news.com.au/business/markets/mike-baird-to-step-down-from-nab-role-c-730352|title=Baird has an \"open mind\" after leaving NAB|date=2020-03-04|website=7NEWS.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> In March 2020, it was reported that Baird would leave the company on April 15, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/banking-and-finance/mike-baird-resigns-from-national-australia-bank-20200305-p5471l.html|title=Mike Baird privately rules out return to politics after quitting NAB|last=Grieve|first=Charlotte|date=2020-03-04|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, Baird was appointed Chief Executive Officer of HammondCare.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/companies/healthcare-and-fitness/mike-baird-to-run-aged-care-provider-hammondcare-20200421-p54lpu|title=Mike Baird to run aged care provider HammondCare|date=2020-04-21|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> \n\n== Personal life ==\nBaird lives in [[Fairlight, New South Wales|Fairlight]] in northern Sydney<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/mike-bairds-wife-kerryn-reveals-what-it-is-like-living-with-the-states-premier/news-story/f0c1163e716755b697063277bc583c3a|accessdate=14 November 2014|date=22 March 2015|first=Kerryn|last=Baird|title=Mike Baird's wife Kerryn reveals what it is like living with the State's Premier|work=Daily Telegraph}}</ref> and is married to wife Kerryn. Together they have three children; Laura, Cate and Luke.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-04/mike-baird-a-day-on-the-election-campaign-with-nsw-premier/6261878|title=NSW election 2015: A day with Premier Mike Baird on the campaign trail|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=4 March 2015|first=Brigid|last=Glanville|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> \n\nHis sister is journalist [[Julia Baird (journalist)|Julia Baird]], presenter of ABC's ''[[The Drum (TV program)|The Drum]]'' TV program. His younger brother, Steve Baird, is an executive at [[Velocity Frequent Flyer]].\n\nBaird is a long time friend of former [[Prime Minister of Australia|Australian prime minister]] [[Tony Abbott]] and they regularly surf together off the [[Northern Beaches]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Biography|Business and economics|Conservatism|Law|New South Wales|Politics}}\n* [[Second Baird ministry|Baird ministry]]\n* [[O'Farrell ministry]]\n* [[Shadow Ministry of Barry O'Farrell]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n&nbsp;\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-nsw-la}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Barr (politician)|David Barr]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Electoral district of Manly|Member for Manly]]|years=2007\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[James Griffin (Australian politician)|James Griffin]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Eric Roozendaal]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Treasurer of New South Wales]]|years=2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrew Constance]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barry O'Farrell]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Premier of New South Wales]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gladys Berejiklian]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Jobs, Investment, Tourism and Western Sydney|Minister for Western Sydney]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stuart Ayres]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brad Hazzard]] |as=Minister for Planning and Infrastructure}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Planning (New South Wales)#Infrastructure|Minister for Infrastructure]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrew Constance]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barry O'Farrell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)|Leader of the New South Wales Liberal Party]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gladys Berejiklian]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Premiers of New South Wales}}\n{{Treasurers of New South Wales}}\n{{Leaders of the New South Wales Liberal Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baird, Mike}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Australian investment bankers]]\n[[Category:Australian republicans]]\n[[Category:Deutsche Bank people]]\n[[Category:HSBC people]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Members of the New South Wales Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Premiers of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Treasurers of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|New South Wales politician and premier}}\n{{about|the Australian politician|other people called Mike or Michael Baird|Michael Baird (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix  = [[The Honourable]]\n| name             = Mike Baird \n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = File:The Honourable Mike Baird MP.png\n| imagesize        =\n| order1           = 44th [[Premier of New South Wales]]<br />{{small|Elections: [[2015 New South Wales state election|2015]]}}\n| term_start1      = 17 April 2014\n| term_end1        = 23 January 2017\n| monarch1         = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| governor1        = [[Marie Bashir]]<br />[[David Hurley]]\n| deputy1          = [[Andrew Stoner]] <br />[[Troy Grant]] <br />[[John Barilaro]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Barry O'Farrell]]\n| successor1       = [[Gladys Berejiklian]]\n| order2           = 20th [[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)#Parliamentary party leaders|Leader of the New South Wales Liberal Party]]\n| term_start2      = 17 April 2014\n| term_end2        = 23 January 2017\n| deputy2          = Gladys Berejiklian\n| predecessor2     = [[Barry O'Farrell]]\n| successor2       = Gladys Berejiklian\n| order3           = [[Minister for Planning (New South Wales)#Infrastructure|Minister for Infrastructure]]\n| term_start3      = 23 April 2014\n| term_end3        = 23 January 2017\n| predecessor3     = [[Brad Hazzard]]\n| successor3       = [[Andrew Constance]]\n| order4           = [[Minister for Jobs, Investment, Tourism and Western Sydney|Minister for Western Sydney]]\n| term_start4      = 23 April 2014\n| term_end4        = 23 January 2017\n| predecessor4     = [[Barry O'Farrell]]\n| successor4       = [[Stuart Ayres]]\n| order5           = [[Treasurer of New South Wales]]\n| term_start5      = 3 April 2011\n| term_end5        = 23 April 2014\n| premier5         = [[Barry O'Farrell]]\n| predecessor5     = [[Eric Roozendaal]]\n| successor5       = [[Andrew Constance]]\n| constituency_MP6 = [[Electoral district of Manly|Manly]]\n| parliament6      = New South Wales\n| term_start6      = [[2007 New South Wales state election|24 March 2007]]\n| term_end6        = 23 January 2017\n| predecessor6     = [[David Barr (politician)|David Barr]]\n| successor6       = [[James Griffin (Australian politician)|James Griffin]]\n| birth_name       = Michael Bruce Baird\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1968|4|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)|Liberal Party]]\n| relations        = [[Bruce Baird]] (father), [[Julia Baird (journalist)|Julia Baird]] (sister)\n| spouse           = Kerryn Baird\n| children         = 3\n| occupation       = [[Chief Customer Officer]] of [[National Australia Bank|NAB]]<br />[[Politician]]\n| religion         = [[Anglican Church of Australia|Anglican]]\n| education        = [[The King's School, Parramatta]]<br />[[University of Sydney]]<br />[[Regent College]]\n| signature        =\n| website          =\n| footnotes        = <ref>{{cite web|last=Korporaal|first=Glenda|title=Political son wants a big gig|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/political-son-wants-a-big-gig/story-fn59niix-1226000008332|work=[[The Australian]]|date=5 February 2011|publisher=News Limited|accessdate=26 April 2011}}</ref><ref name=guardianwhois>{{cite news|last=Jabour|first=Bridie|title=Who is Mike Baird? Meet NSW's new fiscally conservative Christian premier|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/apr/17/who-is-mike-baird-new-nsw-premier|accessdate=17 April 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 April 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Michael Bruce Baird''' (born 1 April 1968<ref>{{cite book |author1=Yeend, Peter Jon |author2=King's School (Parramatta, NSW) Council |title=The King's School register 1831\u20131999 |publication-date=2000 |publisher=Council of the King's School |edition=3rd |isbn=978-0-908234-06-6 }}</ref>) is an [[Australia]]n investment banker and former politician who was the 44th [[Premier of New South Wales]], the Minister for Infrastructure, the [[Minister for Jobs, Investment, Tourism and Western Sydney|Minister for Western Sydney]], and the [[Leader of the New South Wales Liberal Party]] from April 2014 to January 2017.\n\nBaird represented the [[electoral district of Manly]] in the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]] for the [[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)|Liberal Party]] from [[2007 New South Wales state election|2007]] to 2017. Before becoming Premier, he was the [[Treasurer of New South Wales]] in the [[Barry O'Farrell|O'Farrell]] [[O'Farrell ministry|government]] between 2011 and 2014. On 19 January 2017, Baird announced his intention to step down and on 23 January he resigned as Premier and member for Manly.\n\n==Early career==\nBorn in Melbourne, Baird is the son of Judy and [[Bruce Baird]].<ref name=guardianwhois/> His father was Deputy Leader of the New South Wales Liberal Party and Member of Parliament representing the [[electoral district of Northcott]], and later a Member of the [[Australian House of Representatives]], representing the [[Division of Cook]], for the Liberal Party.\n\nBaird attended [[The King's School, Parramatta]],<ref name=thesonrises /> and spent time living in the [[United States of America]] while his father served as head of the Australian trade commission in [[New York City]].<ref name=smhwhois/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sydneyanglicans.net/blogs/indepth/bruce_bairds_sweetest_victory|accessdate=15 November 2015|title=Early starters make real connections|first=Natasha|last=Percy|date=29 January 2009|publisher=Sydney Anglican Network}}</ref> Baird graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] with majors in Economics and Government from the [[University of Sydney]] in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sydney.edu.au/arts/economics/alumni/alumni-profiles.shtml|title=ECONOMICS ALUMNI PROFILES|publisher=The University of Sydney|quote=Mike BAIRD (BA \u201989).<br />Melbourne-born, Baird attended the King\u2019s School, Parramatta before undertaking his Sydney Arts degree with majors in Economics and Government.}}</ref><ref>{{cite NSW Parliament |id=40 |name=Mr (Mike) Michael Bruce BAIRD (1968 - ) |former=Yes |access-date=3 April 2019}}</ref> Baird also studied at [[Regent College]] in [[Vancouver|Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada, initially intending to enter the [[Anglican ministry]], but while there decided to pursue a career in investment banking and later politics.<ref name=thesonrises>{{cite web   | url  =  http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/the-son-rises-20121023-282ga.html   | title = The son rises   | last = Wood   | first = Stephanie   | work = Sydney Morning Herald   | date = 26 October 2012   | accessdate = 17 April 2014}}</ref> In 1999, he unsuccessfully sought preselection for the seat of Manly. Baird then returned to investment banking, working for the [[National Australia Bank]] for a time in [[London]], before returning to Sydney to work for [[HSBC]] Australia.<ref name=WOz-2011/>\n\n==Political career==\nBaird again sought, this time successfully, Liberal Party preselection for the seat of Manly and went on to defeat the sitting independent member [[David Barr (politician)|David Barr]] by 3.4% at the [[2007 New South Wales state election|2007 state election]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mikebaird.com.au/about/mike/about_mike.html |title=About Mike Baird |work=Member for Manly |publisher=Mike Baird |accessdate=11 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218103945/http://www.mikebaird.com.au/about/mike/about_mike.html |archive-date=18 February 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After initially serving in a range of junior shadow ministries, Baird was promoted to the position of Shadow Treasurer in 2008 and touted as a future Liberal leader.<ref name=WOz-2011>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/ex-banker-seeks-to-bring-balance-to-treasury-mike-baird-has-the-background-to-look-after-nsws-finances/story-e6frg8zx-1226028266126 |title=Ex-banker seeks to bring balance to Treasury: Mike Baird has the background to look after NSW's finances |work=[[The Australian|The Weekend Australian]] |date=26 March 2011 |author1=Cleary, Paul |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/ofarrells-heir-apparent-promoted/2008/12/27/1229998798654.html |title=Heir apparent promoted |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=28 December 2008 |author1=Lewis, Daniel |author2=Gibson, Joel |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref> Following the election of the O'Farrell government in 2011, Baird was appointed Treasurer, although O'Farrell removed some of Baird's ministerial responsibilities, transferring the authority for land tax, gaming tax, payroll tax, public service superannuation and the Office of State Revenue to [[Greg Pearce (politician)|Greg Pearce]], the Minister for Finance and Services.<ref name=Oz-2011>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/cupboard-is-baird-for-new-treasurer/story-fn3dxity-1226033790724 |title=Cupboard is Baird for new Treasurer as Barry O'Farrell 'neuters' department |work=[[The Australian]] |date=5 April 2011 |author1=Clennell, Andrew |accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nBaird has campaigned against dangerous drinking, voted against embryonic stem research and euthanasia, does not support same-sex marriage or same-sex adoption<ref name=Onward>{{cite news |last=Nicholls |first=Sean |date=26 April 2014 |title=Onward Christian soldier: a premier's faith |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/onward-christian-soldier-a-premiers-faith-20140425-379pp.html |newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald }}</ref><ref name=smhwhois>{{cite news |author=Howden, Saffron |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/who-is-mike-baird-20140417-36ssh.html#ixzz2z5vnhpts |title=Who is Mike Baird? |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=17 April 2014 |accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref> and has stated that his strongest preference is not to support abortion in most circumstances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/the-new-face-of-the-liberals-charm-offensive/2008/12/29/1230399131583.html|title=The new face of the Liberals' charm offensive|last=Robins|first=Brian|date=30 December 2008|accessdate=24 February 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> He is strongly in favour of [[Republicanism in Australia|Australia becoming a republic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/apr/18/mike-baird-admits-mistake-appoint-nick-di-girolamo|title=Mike Baird admits mistake to appoint Nick de Girolamo to Sydney Water|last=Jabour|first=Bridie|work=The Guardian|date=18 April 2014|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Baird supported calls for increasing the [[Goods and Services Tax (Australia)|GST]] to 15%<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/tony-abbott-applauds-premier-mike-bairds-15-gst-proposal-20150720-gig34f.html</ref><ref>http://www.news.com.au/finance/economy/australian-economy/would-you-pay-more-push-to-raise-gst-to-15-per-cent/news-story/5b56a0ca3f2766e4d17ac567b7d1cce5</ref>\n\n===Premier of New South Wales===\n{{see also|Baird ministry (2014\u201315)|Second Baird ministry}}\n[[Image:(1)Lindt_Cafe_Reopening_035.jpg|thumb|left|Baird at the official [[2014 Sydney hostage crisis|reopening of the Lindt Caf\u00e9, Martin Place]], Sydney, March 2015.]]\n\nFollowing Barry O'Farrell's resignation,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/barry-ofarrell-quits-as-nsw-premier-over-memory-fail/story-fn59niix-1226886224077 |title=Barry O'Farrell quits as NSW Premier over memory fail |date=16 April 2014 |work=[[The Australian]] |accessdate=23 April 2014|first1=Leo|last1=Shanahan|first2=Mark|last2=Coultan}}</ref> Baird was elected unopposed as parliamentary leader of the NSW division of the Liberal Party on 17 April 2014, and subsequently sworn in as the 44th Premier of New South Wales on 23 April by the [[Governor of New South Wales]], [[Marie Bashir|Dame Marie Bashir]].<ref name=libleader>{{cite news|title=Mike Baird named new NSW premier named after Barry O'Farrell resignation|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-04-17/new-nsw-premier-named-after-ofarrell-resignation/5396584|accessdate=17 April 2014|newspaper=ABC News|date=17 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nBaird immediately reshuffled the ministry elevating [[Andrew Constance]] into the [[Treasurer of New South Wales|Treasury]] portfolio and increasing [[Andrew Stoner]]'s ministries to five <ref name=reshuffle>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/mike-bairds-cabinet-reshuffle-a-preparation-for-next-election-20140422-371g9.html?rand=1398136093991|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=14 November 2015|date=22 April 2014|title=Mike Baird's cabinet reshuffle a preparation for next election|first=Sean|last=Nicholls}}</ref> in preparation for the [[2015 New South Wales state election|2015 state election]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/mike-bairds-nsw-cabinet-20140422-371j4.html |title=Mike Baird's NSW cabinet |date=22 April 2014 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate=23 April 2014 }}</ref><ref name=reshuffle/> In October, Stoner resigned as Leader of the NSW Nationals and [[Deputy Premier of New South Wales]] and was replaced by [[Troy Grant]].\n\nThe ''Sydney Morning Herald'' described Baird's government as \"the most devout in living memory,\" with a concentration of powerful religious figures in its upper echelons.<ref name=Onward/> Baird's chief of staff, Bay Warburton, once said that in his role as chief of staff he is serving Jesus, \"and Mike (Baird), who's the Treasurer\u2014he believes he's serving Jesus as the Treasurer of the state. He believes that he has a great opportunity to help people by making responsible decisions about the money from this state.\"<ref name=Onward/>\n\nOn the morning of 15 December 2014, a lone gunman, [[Man Haron Monis]], [[2014 Sydney hostage crisis|held hostage ten customers and eight employees]] of a [[Lindt & Spr\u00fcngli|Lindt]] chocolate caf\u00e9 located at [[Martin Place, Sydney]]. Baird addressed the media during the stand-off, and stated \"we are being tested today... in Sydney. The police are being tested, the public is being tested, but whatever the test we will face it head on and we will remain a strong democratic, civil society. I have full confidence in the [[List of Commissioners of New South Wales Police|Police Commissioner]] and the incredible work of the [[New South Wales Police Force|NSW police force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QXYrHlBPX-k|title=Premier and Commissioner address the media re: Martin Place police operation|work=YouTube|accessdate=15 December 2014|date=15 December 2014}}</ref> On 20 March 2015, Baird met with staff at the re-opened caf\u00e9, stating the staff and company: \"...Are saying that they want to be strong for their friends, they want to be strong for this city and state\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-20/lindt-cafe-in-martin-place-reopens-after-deadly-siege/6334154|work=ABC News|title=Lindt cafe in Sydney's Martin Place reopens after deadly siege|first=Johanna|last=Nicholson|date=20 March 2015|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2015 New South Wales election====\n{{see also|New South Wales state election, 2015}}\n\nAt the 2015 election, Baird led the Liberal-National Coalition to a second term. The main policy that dominated the election was Baird's unpopular policy to lease 49% of the state's electricity distribution network, known as the \"poles and wires\" in the form of a 99-year lease to the private sector and use the proceeds to invest in new road, public transport, water, health and education infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/mike-bairds-electricity-dilemma-popular-premier-selling-a-toxic-electricity-privatisation-policy-20150306-13x13f.html|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=14 November 2014|date=7 March 2015|first1=Matt|last1=Wade|first2=Sean|last2=Nicholls|title=Mike Baird's electricity dilemma: popular Premier selling a toxic electricity privatisation policy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afr.com/news/coalition-premier-mike-baird-wins-nsw-election-20150328-1m9zxo|title=Coalition Premier Mike Baird wins NSW election|work=Financial Review|first1=Aaron|last1=Patrick|first2=Geoff|last2=Winestock|first3=Will|last3=Glasgow}}</ref>\n\nOther regional policies centred around the Baird Government's truncation of the [[Central Coast & Newcastle Line|Central Coast & Newcastle Railway Line]] at [[Wickham railway station, New South Wales|Wickham]] and its replacement with the $130 million [[Newcastle Light Rail|light rail system]] and associated [[Newcastle Interchange|transport interchange]] as part of a broader revitilisation of the [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]] city centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/nsw-state-election-2015/nsw-state-election-2015-the-train-that-divides-newcastle-20150225-13oflk.html|title=NSW State Election 2015: The train that divides Newcastle|first=Eryk|last=Bagshaw|date=4 March 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Heraldl|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref> [[Coal Seam Gas]] was a likewise major regional issue in northern New South Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-15/nationals-face-csg-backlash-northern-nsw-state-election/6319350|accessdate=14 November 2015|date=15 March 2015|work=ABC news|title=NSW election 2015: Nationals on edge in state's north over CSG backlash|first=Bruce|last=MacKenzie}}</ref>\n\nUltimately, Baird won a full term, though he lost 15 seats from the massive majority he'd inherited from O'Farrell. Baird is only the fourth state Liberal leader, after Sir [[Robert Askin]], [[Nick Greiner]] and O'Farrell, to win an election in New South Wales since the main non-Labor party adopted the [[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)|Liberal]] banner in 1945. It also marked the first time since [[1973 New South Wales state election|1973]] that a non-Labor government had retained its majority at an election and Baird became the first non-elected Liberal Premier to be elected in his own right.\n\n====Approval rating====\nSince replacing Barry O'Farrell as Premier in April 2014, Baird initially fared well in statewide opinion polls but his approval rating collapsed in the 2nd half of 2016. From December 2015 to September 2016, Baird's satisfaction rating fell by 46 points\u2014\"the biggest fall in net satisfaction of any mainland state premier in the history of Newspoll\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/newspoll/newspoll-dogs-ban-sends-mike-baird-ratings-into-freefall/news-story/91294495701cb40234d342cabd8c103b|first=Mark|last=Coultan|date=29 September 2016|work=The Australian|accessdate=1 December 2016|title=Newspoll: Dogs Ban Sends Mike Baird's Ratings Into Freefall}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:left; text-align:center; margin-right:.5em; margin-top:.4em; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n|+ '''Newspoll <br /> Satisfaction Rating of Mike Baird'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/state-politics/mike-baird-slumps-to-lowest-rating-as-coalition-clings-to-its-lead/news-story/3d2725e40d1cf002daa20eb9ce63186c|title=Mike Baird slumps to lowest rating as Coalition clings to its lead|work=The Australian|date=8 December 2016|first=Kylar|last=Loussikian|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n!\n! Satisfied\n! Dissatisfied \n|-\n! September 2016\n| style=|39%\n| style=|46% \n|-\n! September 2015\n| style=|63%\n| style=|23% \n|-   \n! March 2015\n| style=|57%\n| style=|29% \n|- \n! February 2015\n| style=|59%\n| style=|26% \n|- \n! December 2014\n| style=|60%\n| style=|22% \n|- \n! October 2014\n| style=|56%\n| style=|20% \n|- \n! August 2014\n| style=|49%\n| style=|23% \n|- \n! June 2014\n| style=|49%\n| style=|19% \n|- \n|}\n{{Clear}}\n\n====Lockout laws====\nBaird had publicly advocated for the tough [[Sydney lockout laws]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nsw.gov.au/newlaws |title=New alcohol laws now in place ShareTweet Sydney's alcohol laws |publisher=NSW Government |accessdate=21 Feb 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223141047/http://www.nsw.gov.au/newlaws |archivedate=23 February 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and on 9&nbsp;February 2016 posted a [[Facebook]] response to an article published by [[Matt Barrie]] condemning the Premier's actions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/matt-barries-tirade-against-sydneys-nighttime-regulations-goes-viral-20160203-gmlab1.html |title=Matt Barrie's tirade against Sydney's night-time lockout laws touches a raw nerve |publisher=Fairfax Media|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=21 Feb 2016|first=Daisy|last=Dumas}}</ref> Baird's response gained international attention<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-australia-35499522 |title=Sydney's lockout \u2018laughing stock' |publisher=BBC |accessdate=21 Feb 2016}}</ref> after the post received over 10,000 likes - along with more than 10,000 comments that were mostly critical of the Premier's stance on the laws.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/lockout-laws-nsw-premier-mike-baird-bombarded-on-facebook-and-twitter/news-story/0f627e978dd2002d9a86db9f460da65e |title=Lockout laws: NSW Premier Mike Baird bombarded on Facebook and Twitter |publisher=The Australian |accessdate=21 February 2016|first=Fred|last=Pawle|date=10 February 2016}}</ref> Baird's reputation as a \"darling of social media\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/thefeed/article/2016/02/10/mike-bairds-run-social-media-darling-goes-bust-casinomike |title=Mike Baird\u2019s run as social media darling goes bust with #casinomike |publisher=SBS |accessdate=21 February 2016|first=Maddie|last=Palmer|date=10 February 2016}}</ref> was tarnished as the hashtag #casinomike became the number one trending topic nationwide on [[Twitter]] in reference to lockout laws not applying to [[The Star, Sydney|Star City Casino]], as it is located outside the entertainment and cbd precincts where the laws apply.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/lockout-laws-star-attraction-inside-sydneys-biggest-afterhours-venue/news-story/521a30d553ce92b113b0c01178c34501 |title=Lockout laws\u2019 Star attraction: Inside Sydney\u2019s biggest after-hours venue|publisher=News.com |accessdate=21 February 2016|date=15 February 2016|first1=Emma|last1=Reynolds|first2=Andrew|last2=Koubaridis}}</ref> A protest was organised in response to Baird's comments by community group Keep Sydney Open on 21 February 2016,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/keep-sydney-open-protesters-march-to-unlock-sydneys-nightlife-20160221-gmzggk.html |title=Keep Sydney Open: protesters march to 'unlock Sydney's nightlife |publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=21 February 2016|first=Patrick|last=Begley|date=21 February 2016}}</ref> with over 15,000 people marching in Sydney's CBD and calling on the Baird government to abolish the lockout laws.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com.au/photos-15000-people-protest-lockout-laws-in-keep-sydney-open-rally-2016-2 |title=Photos: 15,000 people protest lockout laws in Keep Sydney Open rally |publisher=The Business Insider |accessdate=21 February 2016|first=Olivia|last=Chang|date=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Resignation====\nOn 19 January 2017, Baird announced he was retiring from politics, with his resignation to be effective after a [[leadership spill]] the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thesatellite.com.au/news/baird-resigns-nsw-premier-quit-top-job-and-parliam/3133375/|first=Owen|last=Jacques|title=Baird resigns: NSW Premier to quit top job and Parliament|work=The Satellite|date=19 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202002956/http://m.thesatellite.com.au/news/baird-resigns-nsw-premier-quit-top-job-and-parliam/3133375/|archivedate=2 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He said, \"I have made clear from the beginning that I was in politics to make a difference, and then move on. After 10 years in public life, this moment for me has arrived.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.9news.com.au/national/2017/01/19/09/08/nsw-premier-mike-baird-announces-resignation|work=9 News|date=19 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2017|title=NSW Premier Mike Baird brought to tears as he explains why he\u2019s quitting politics|first=Mary|last=Jordan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/politics/premier-mike-baird-resigns/news-story/c23b24d808dccecc654741106f9f64f7|title=Premier Mike Baird resigns|first=Kim|last=Stephens|work=news.com.au|date=19 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref> Following his decision to resign, Baird was criticised for his failure to listen on key issues such as protests against the [[WestConnex]], lockout laws and [[Local government areas of New South Wales#2010s|local government amalgamations]]. Baird also reversed an earlier decision to ban greyhound racing in the face of significant community pressure, especially from the Nationals.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Fernandez, Timothy |author2=Vukovic, Dom |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-01-20/mike-baird-resignation-thoughts-from-protesters-and-haters/8195434 |title=Mike Baird resignation: Thoughts from protesters and haters |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=20 January 2017 |access-date=23 January 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January 2017, Baird formally resigned as both premier and member for Manly, and [[Gladys Berejiklian]] was sworn in as New South Wales' 45th premier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-01-23/gladys-berejiklian-replaces-mike-baird-as-nsw-premier/8202820|title=Gladys Berejiklian is Premier of New South Wales, replacing Mike Baird|first=Clare|last=Blumer|date=23 January 2017|accessdate=26 January 2017|work=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n== Return to corporate life ==\nIn February 2017, Baird was appointed Chief Customer Officer at [[National Australia Bank]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-02-28/mike-baird-former-nsw-premier-takes-senior-nab-role/8309516|title=Mike Baird moves to NAB: Former NSW premier takes senior bank role|first=Michael|last=Janda|publisher=ABC|date=28 February 2017}}</ref> Baird was paid a total of A$2.29 million in 2018. In 2019, NAB executives forfeited their short-term bonuses, resulting in Baird earning the lesser total of A$1.7 million for that year. At the end of the 2018/2019 financial year, Baird held A$500,000 of NAB stock as well as 67,888 NAB performance rights, worth A$1.59 million as of March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://7news.com.au/business/markets/mike-baird-to-step-down-from-nab-role-c-730352|title=Baird has an \"open mind\" after leaving NAB|date=2020-03-04|website=7NEWS.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> In March 2020, it was reported that Baird would leave the company on April 15, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/banking-and-finance/mike-baird-resigns-from-national-australia-bank-20200305-p5471l.html|title=Mike Baird privately rules out return to politics after quitting NAB|last=Grieve|first=Charlotte|date=2020-03-04|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, it was announced that Baird would commence as CEO of HammondCare. \n\n== Personal life ==\nBaird lives in [[Fairlight, New South Wales|Fairlight]] in northern Sydney<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/mike-bairds-wife-kerryn-reveals-what-it-is-like-living-with-the-states-premier/news-story/f0c1163e716755b697063277bc583c3a|accessdate=14 November 2014|date=22 March 2015|first=Kerryn|last=Baird|title=Mike Baird's wife Kerryn reveals what it is like living with the State's Premier|work=Daily Telegraph}}</ref> and is married to wife Kerryn. Together they have three children; Laura, Cate and Luke.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-04/mike-baird-a-day-on-the-election-campaign-with-nsw-premier/6261878|title=NSW election 2015: A day with Premier Mike Baird on the campaign trail|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=4 March 2015|first=Brigid|last=Glanville|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> \n\nHis sister is journalist [[Julia Baird (journalist)|Julia Baird]], presenter of ABC's ''[[The Drum (TV program)|The Drum]]'' TV program. His younger brother, Steve Baird, is an executive at [[Velocity Frequent Flyer]].\n\nBaird is a long time friend of former [[Prime Minister of Australia|Australian prime minister]] [[Tony Abbott]] and they regularly surf together off the [[Northern Beaches]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Biography|Business and economics|Conservatism|Law|New South Wales|Politics}}\n* [[Second Baird ministry|Baird ministry]]\n* [[O'Farrell ministry]]\n* [[Shadow Ministry of Barry O'Farrell]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n&nbsp;\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-nsw-la}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Barr (politician)|David Barr]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Electoral district of Manly|Member for Manly]]|years=2007\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[James Griffin (Australian politician)|James Griffin]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Eric Roozendaal]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Treasurer of New South Wales]]|years=2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrew Constance]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barry O'Farrell]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Premier of New South Wales]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gladys Berejiklian]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Jobs, Investment, Tourism and Western Sydney|Minister for Western Sydney]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stuart Ayres]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brad Hazzard]] |as=Minister for Planning and Infrastructure}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Planning (New South Wales)#Infrastructure|Minister for Infrastructure]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrew Constance]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barry O'Farrell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Liberal Party of Australia (New South Wales Division)|Leader of t